to look, or look at. Vĭdeo, aspĭcio, 3; prospĭcio, intueor, 2; specto, 1.—
To look after; i. e. manage, cūro, 1; dīrĭgo, 3.—To look down, or down
upon, lit. Despēcto, lit. and metaph. despĭcio. See to despise.—To lok
for; i. e. seek, q. v.; quæro, 3; exqulro.—To look forward, prospĭcio,
prospecto.—To look into; i. e. examine, investĭgo, 1.—To look out, it
take care, caveo, 2.—To look over, as an overseer, præsum; i. e. to pardon,
ignosco, 3.—To look round, round upon, &c., circumspicio, collustro, 1.—
To look to; i. e. regard, q. v., respicio.—To look up, up to, lit. and
metaph., inspĭcio. See to respect.—It is easy to look around you.
Facilis est circumspectus.

to lose. Perdo, 3; amitto, 3. [Amitto is used of what we lose by the
fault of others, and of what is recoverable; perdo, of what we lose by our
own folly, and what is irrecoverable. In one place, Cic. says, Decius lost
his life, but did not throw it away. Decius amisit vitam at non perdidit.]
—I am losing my time. Frustra tempus contero. Cic.—Volumnius
said, that he had rather that his labour should have been lost. Volum-
nins dixit se malle frustra operam insumtam. Liv.—The bill which he
willingly allowed to be lost. Lex quam antiquari facile passus est
Cic.—What more could you ask if you had lost your own camp? Quid
alind si spoliatus, si exutus castris esses, peteres? Liv.—The enemy for
the same reason lost all hope of taking the town. Hostibus eâdem de
causâ spes potiendi oppidi discessit. Cic.—We have lost a great battle.
Pugnâ magnâ victi sumus. Cic.
